Author: riku#6996
Content:
> then deploying that container under a sub domain
@Snu traefik is your friend

Author: riku#6996
Content: and then just link it with a script to your dns provider's api

Author: riku#6996
Content: use Traefik instead of nginx so you can have your new subdomains automatically configured at your host level (so your machine is listening + automatic LetsEncrypt) - traefik dynamically updates based on labels you set on docker containers

Author: riku#6996
Content: and then use something like this to automatically update your DNS records: https://github.com/tiredofit/docker-traefik-cloudflare-companion

Author: riku#6996
Content: documentation is kinda annoying (at first) but 100% worth the switch if you use docker based deployments

Author: Snu#0167
Content: damn this is actually hella cool

Author: riku#6996
Content: definitely not during a late night hacking spree

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: I might even use this for my server

Author: riku#6996
Content: ye, the only annoying thing is repeating labels tbh lol (it's out of necessity, but annoying)

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Does the interface have an API, too?

Author: riku#6996
Content: yeah the interface actually just interacts with the api im pretty sure

Content: Then you can make a CLI to script deploys from local projects

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001

Author: riku#6996
Content: @Storm_FireFox1 are you talking about using the api to tell traefik about a new deploy? traefik would already detect that to begin with, no?

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Stanley was talking about an automatic deploy of a local project to a reverse proxy

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content:
So, for instance, if I run "npm deploy":
- compile Docker image / whatever I can do to reproduce a build on the server
- get files on the server
- get subdomain for project
- get HTTPS certificate
- deploy to subdomain

Author: riku#6996
Content: uh i mean in the case of traefik, all you would need to do is compile and build your docker image and attach labels to the container when you boot it up

Author: riku#6996
Content: traefik would automatically detect it and handle the rest

Author: riku#6996
Content: assuming you deploy your project into a new running docker container, traefik would detect the new container and automatically deploy it to whatever subdomain you indicated in the labels and automatically fetch https certs too

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: It was more that the issue is, I can't see if Traefik can automatically see new spawned container not in the Docker Compose file

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Eitehr that, or you were right about the documentation sucking

Author: riku#6996
Content: it doesn't really have anything to do with Docker compose tbh

Author: riku#6996
Content: Traefik listens to Docker itself - it knows exactly when new containers are spawned, destroyed, etc

Author: riku#6996
Content: that's what makes it so nice - it's completely dynamic

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: And then it reads whatever is there

Author: riku#6996
Content: if you deploy a new container with the appropriate traefik labels, traefik will dynamically update its own internal configuration to act as a reverse proxy + load balancer to your container

Author: riku#6996
Content: no need to ever talk to traefik to begin with

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Alright, so deploys would just devolve to running a Docker container with specific labels on the host machine

Author: riku#6996
Content: and you can use that Cloudflare DNS thing earlier or anything else to have your DNS records automatically updated too (obviously this isn't Traefik native functionality, as Traefik itself is only designed to be a reverse proxy / etc)

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content:
So use the Cloudflare config and you just get a nice:
```ssh traefikhost "docker run some_project --label traefik.enable=true --label ..."```

Author: riku#6996
Content: yep, and the rest should be taken care of for you (assuming no errors)

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: Is Zoom's security mediocre? Yes, but that's just what you get because security and ease of use almost never mix (never underestimate how difficult it is for people to use the most basic things). Are the issues also pretty overblown (comparative to the amount of media attention they got)? Also yes. Deadass there were articles about "Zoom recordings publicly uploaded to the internet for all to see" and literally the issue there was that okay, Zoom uses a standardized format when it exports media recordings and then people uploaded those to Google Drive or Dropbox and turned on public sharing, and somehow overzealous media reporting turned that into a __Zoom__ security issue instead of a "people being dumb" issue.

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: No end-to-end encryption on conference calls companies use (which they most likely assumed remained confidential) is a big no-no

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Also, the fact it's closed source isn't helping its case when it comes to the grassroots tech people

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: So both sides of the tech world were pissed about the security

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content:
> No end-to-end encryption on conference calls companies use (which they most likely assumed remained confidential) is a big no-no
@Storm_FireFox1 it's pretty damn difficult to do e2e encryption on a videoconfrencing service that's easy for non-tech people to use (security and ease of use, like i said, tend not to mix)

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: When your service is being used by mothers that you have to teach how to copy an image from Google Images to PowerPoint, you start to become __very__ sensitive to ease of use concerns

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: Do you have any idea how long it took me to teach my mom how to use Zoom? And she still can't do anything on it apart from start a call and share her screen, and she still screws that up frequently.

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: People are far more tech illiterate than anyone expects, and I have learned that you can never be not surprised at how people struggle with these things.

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: Signal has E2EE, and I think it's pretty easy to use

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: E2EE has virtually no relevance on ease of use, but admittedly, the focus of Zoom's dev team would be on that rather than security

Content:

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001

Author: Storm_FireFox1#0001
Content: If I was gonna give an example of a good chat app that had that on desktop and mobile, I'd recommend Matrix, but Matrix is not even **remotely** close to being used by your average person (even if it is easy to use)

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content:
Signal really falls apart when it comes to usage on multiple devices too (which is something many people would expect)

Like I actually went and evaluated Signal with a group of friends and we all collectively decided against it because Signal's multi-device support is... mediocre at best

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: so a lot of the e2e focused apps do have a lot of usability concerns in general

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: For all its (mediocre at best) security, Telegram gets usability right down to the core

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: Also signal doesn’t support groups so... e2e gets a lot harder with group video
